pr_review_comment_body:
I think it should be:

    return _path_re.sub('', module_path).replace(os.path.sep, '.').replace('/', '.')

Because what if there are multiple `slashes, like `X:\path\to\something/foo/bar.py`?

Possibly, but this module is more intended to detect issues with the arguments rather than the template itself. These templates are more or less coming from proto files which are separately validated. Asserting that a given path template itself is valid would require a lexer/parser which is really what we wanted to avoid.

In a lot of these cases this module won't balk at these strings:

> /v1/***

is recognized as having two positional args, the first one is multi-segment and the second is single-segment.

> /v1/{{foo
> /v1/{}
> /v1/}
> /v1/{fo/o}
> /v1/{name={

Are all considered to not have any variables.

> /v1/{**}

is a fun case because it'll expect a named variable called `**` (which is possible to specify with `expand(tmpl, **{'**': 'value'})`. (I love this one)

